However, in the context of a steroidal framework, the 3-oxo group can participate in hydrogen bonding with adjacent hydrogens which could either raise or slightly lower the melting point. Steric hindrance might reduce the effective hydrogen bonding. For ketones on steroids, this effect might be around +5 to -5°C. -17-yl formate (ester group): Esters usually have lower melting points than the corresponding acids due to their inability to form strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds like carboxylic acids. This could be estimated at around -10°C. Considering both modifications, we might predict a slight decrease overall.
Prediction: Considering the effects of the keto and ester functional groups on the parent steroidal structure: Androstane melting point reference: ~181°C Keto group adjustment: -5 to +5°C (minimal effect due to steric hindrance with potential hydrogen bonding) Ester group adjustment: -10°C (reduced polarity and flexibility of the formate group) Prediction for 3-oxoandrostan-17-yl formate: 181 + (-5 to +5) - 10 = 166 to 176°C

- 17-yl formate (ester group): Esters tend to decrease the melting point compared to carboxylic acids because they cannot form strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds.
